Package/Project-level Issues

Assuming no "Package" files; all deps info in tooltree.mk

build/tooltree.mk
   packages.mk
      package source/export locations
      package dependencies [future]
   defs.mk
      utilities (--> minion)
      minion classes
      Alias(all)
      Alias(tree)
      build = $(eval include $(builddir)/minion.mk)
      process package info
   config.mk
      Variants.all

PKG/Makefile
   Target Defs
   [this_package = PKG]
   include-deps = ...
   #include ../build/tooltree.mk

tooltree/Makefile:  (just like a package)
   Target Defs -- Alias(default).in = Alias(tree)
   this_package = tooltree
   (no include-deps)
   #incude build/tooltree.mk

EXTERNAL.mk =
   local package info
     PKG-package = DIR
     PKG-outdir = ...
     PKG-deps = ...
   Target Defs
   Config / tooltree-NOCONFIG = 1  ... or Variants.all ?
   [this_package = EXTERNAL]
   include-deps = ...
   #include ...tooltree/build/tooltree.mk


 Problem: `make tree` fails if included makefiles are not yet built
  - Not a problem for tooltree/Makefile
  - Big problem for EXTERNAL.mk; minor annoyance for tooltree packages
  - `.includeFiles` property to be checked prior to every built instance?
  - special-case when only  'tree' & "external" targets are given?


----------------------------------------------------------------
Crank vs. Minion:
 - Crank demanded to know about all potential rules.  This involved:
    - user explicitly declares instances:  Class += I1 I2 ...
    - classes inherit from Gen
    - crank inspects $(.VARIABLES)
    - inferredClasses was an afterthought
   And enabled:
    - `make [targetFile]` would work
    - ALL rules are cached; no need for minion_cache
   But...
    - In the end, this obscured what was built and when.

   Minion understands the dependencies between instances.  Instances can be
   named as inputs or other dependencies, and Minion automatically
   translates them to output file names in the appropriate contexts.
   An instance's rule is expanded only when that instance is referenced
   by one of the current build goals.

   In Crank, we would lean on classes not just as types, but as collections
   of files.  Also, dependencies *on* items were often handled as side
   effects, or upside-down.  Class names were available as phony targets,
   and were implicitly a preqreq of "all" (the default goal), or perhaps
   some other target specified by the `prereqOf` property.

      CC += foo.c bar.c                    # must be named
      Exe.in = ... $(call get,out,CC) ...  # accepts files, not items
      Exe += prog

   Instead, in Minion:

      Alias(default).in = Exe(@prog)
      prog = foo.c bar.c

   Minion understands {PROP} syntax in property definitions.  Ingredient
   lists can use indirection syntax (@var or CLASS@var).  Instances can
   accept multiple arguments.

   Crank supported `inferredItems` as an afterthought.


